body:
Now that this interface is so trivial, and no longer has a class associated with it, or any functionality, I think we should reconsider whether we want it to be "generic". We originally made it a "value" tree instead of a "label" tree because then other features could possibly use it in the future. This made sense because we had implemented various methods and logic and it's nice to re-use those and make them into a "mini library". 

However, this is now nothing more than a type with two properties. In which case, I think the benefits of having nice names/docs that are specific to the transaction feature outweighs it being generic. If you agree, I'd suggest something like:

```ts
interface LabelTree {
  label: unknown;
  sublabels: LabelTree[];
}
```

This may also let you move some of the documentation. I expect some things you had to write out on the long `labels` doc comment can be moved to this type and its properties, and you can link to it.

